      jacketquotes:
        '&ldquo;Extraordinary storytelling at its very best.&rdquo; <i>&mdash;The Detroit Free Press</i>&#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Superb . . . all-stops-out thrilling.&rdquo; <i>&mdash;The Washington Post</i><br> &#160;<br> "Very grand indeed." <i>&mdash;The New York Times</i><br> &#160;<br> "Powerful [&hellip;] a fantasy adventure that sparkles with childlike wonder." <i>&mdash;The Boston Sunday Globe</i><br> &#160;<br> "Marvelous [&hellip;]&#160; the writing is elegant and challenging."&#160;<i>&mdash;The New Yorker</i><br> &#160;<br> "Arguably the best juvenile fantasy novel of the past twenty years [&hellip;]&#160; If [<i>The Subtle Knife</i>] is as good as <i>The Golden Compass,</i> we\'ll be two thirds of the way to the completion of a modern fantasy classic." <br> <i>&mdash;The Washington Post Book World</i><br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Pullman is quite possibly a genius&hellip;using the lineaments of fantasy to tell the truth about the universal experience of growing up.&rdquo;&#160; &mdash;<i>Newsweek</i><br><br>"Masterful storytelling [&hellip;]&#160; with a cast of instantly beguiling characters."&#160;<i>&mdash;The Dallas Morning News</i><br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;The most magnificent fantasy series since Lord of the Rings.&rdquo;&#160; &mdash;<i>The Oregonian<br></i><br> &ldquo;Pullman has created the last great fantasy masterpiece of the twentieth century.&#160; An astounding achievement.&rdquo;&#160; &mdash;<i>The Cincinnati Enquirer<br></i><br> "Once in a lifetime a children\'s author emerges who is so extraordinary that the imagination of generations is altered. Lewis Carroll, E. Nesbit, C.S. Lewis, and Tolkien were all of this cast. So, too, is Philip Pullman, whose Dark Materials trilogy will be devoured by anyone between eight and eighty. The most ambitious work since The Lord of the Rings, it is as intellectually thrilling as it is magnificently written."&#160;<i>&mdash;&#160;New Statesman</i><br> &#160;<br> "Thrillingly paced and exotic [&hellip;] breathtaking."&#160;<i>&mdash;&#160;Columbus Dispatch</i><br><br> &ldquo;[&hellip;] a rare few have minds capacious enough to engage in vast cosmos-making, imagining realms and inventing universes. I am thinking of Dante and Milton and Blake. We may now add Philip Pullman.&rdquo;<i> </i><br> <i>&mdash;Parents Choice (online)</i><br> &#160;<br> "<i>The Golden Compass</i> is one of the best fantasy/adventure stories that I have read in years. This is a book no one should miss." &mdash;Terry Brooks, author of <i>The Sword of Shannara</i><br><br> "As always, Pullman is a master at combining impeccable characterizations and seamless plotting, maintaining a crackling pace to create scene upon scene of almost unbearable tension.&#160;&#160;This glittering gem will leave readers of all ages eagerly awaiting the next installment of Lyra\'s adventures." <br> <i>&mdash;Publishers Weekly</i>, Starred Review<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;This first fantastic installment of the His Dark Materials trilogy propels readers along with horror and high adventure, a shattering tale that begins with a promise and delivers an entire universe.&rdquo; <i>&ndash; Kirkus Reviews,</i> Starred Review<br> &#160;<br> "This first fantastic installment propels readers along with horror and high adventure [&hellip;] A shattering tale that begins with a promise and delivers an entire universe."&#160;<i>&mdash;Kirkus Reviews</i>, Starred<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;The characters of Lord Asriel, Mrs. Coutler, and Iorek Byrnison and the cold and beautiful Northern setting are captivating; the constantly twisting plot and escalating suspense are riveting; and Lyra and Pantalaimon are among the gutsiest and wiliest of adventurers. Touching, exciting, and mysterious by turns, this is a splendid work.&rdquo; &mdash;<i>The Horn Book Magazine,</i> Starred <br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Glorious. And what an ending &mdash; simply operatic.&rdquo; &mdash;<i>School Library Journal,</i> Top 100 Children&rsquo;s Novels (#28)<br> &#160;<br> "This is a captivating fantasy, filled with excitement, suspense, and unusual characters."&#160;<i>&mdash;School Library Journal</i><br> &#160;<br> "A totally involving, intricately plotted fantasy that will leave readers clamoring for the sequels."&#160;<br> <i>&mdash;Booklist, Starred review</i><br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Glorious. . . . <i>The Golden Compass </i>is one of those lyrical suspensions like <i>Alice in Wonderland</i> and <i>The Lord of the Rings</i> that crosses all age lines and intertwines mythologies and legends with seamless beauty.&rdquo; &mdash;<i>BookPage </i>',
