      division: "RH Childrens Books",
      excerpt:
        "CHAPTER ONE<br><br><br> The Last Unicorn<br> &#160;<br> The November sky was gray with clouds. Jack sat reading in front of the living room fire.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Who wants hot chocolate?&rdquo; his dad called from the kitchen.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Me, please!&rdquo; said Jack.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> The front door burst open, and with a gust of cold wind, Annie rushed inside. &ldquo;Jack! Guess what!&rdquo; she whispered. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s back!&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;How do you know?&rdquo; said Jack.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;I was walking home from the library&rdquo;&mdash; Annie paused to catch her breath&mdash;&ldquo;and I saw a flash in the sky above the woods. The last time that happened&mdash;&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> Before she could finish the sentence, Jack jumped up. &ldquo;Dad, Annie and I are going to go outside for a while!&rdquo; he shouted. &ldquo;Can the hot chocolate wait till we get back?&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Sure, have fun!&rdquo; their dad called from the kitchen.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;I have to get my pack,&rdquo; Jack said to Annie. &ldquo;Meet you on the porch.&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t forget the rhyme book!&rdquo; said Annie.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> Annie slipped outside and Jack ran up to his room. He grabbed his backpack. He checked to make sure their book of magic rhymes was inside. <i>Good</i>, there it was.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> Jack charged back downstairs. He pulled on his boots, put on his jacket, tied a scarf around his neck, grabbed his mittens, and headed out the door.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Come on!&rdquo; said Annie.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> Jack could see his breath in the cold air. &ldquo;Brrr,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Let&rsquo;s hurry!&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> Jack and Annie ran down the street and into the Frog Creek woods. They wove between the trees, their boots crunching through the fallen leaves.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> Jack stopped. The magic tree house was back. High in a tall oak tree, it was silhouetted against the gray November sky. &ldquo;You were right,&rdquo; he said to Annie. &ldquo;Good work.&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Thanks,&rdquo; Annie said. She ran to the rope ladder and started up. Jack followed her.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> When they climbed inside the tree house, Jack and Annie saw a book and a scroll of parchment paper lying on the floor. Annie picked up the scroll, unrolled it, and read aloud.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> <i>Dear Jack and Annie of Frog Creek,</i><br> <i>I am sending you on one more mission to prove that you can use magic wisely. This poem will guide you.</i><br> <i>&mdash;M.</i><br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> <i>The very last unicorn </i><br><i> Is now hidden well</i><br><i> By those who have put him </i><br><i> Under a spell.</i><br> &#160;<br><i> Four centuries, four decades </i><br><i> From that afternoon,</i><br><i> At the end of November, </i><br><i> Before the blue moon,</i><br> &#160;<br><i> He will wake once more </i><br><i> And be free to go home </i><br><i> If you call out his name: </i><br><i> Divine Flower of Rome.</i><br> &#160;<br><i> You must coax him to stand </i><br><i> Once his name is spoken.</i><br><i> His chain will break</i><br><i> And the spell, too, be broken.</i><br> &#160;<br><i> Then a young girl must love him </i><br><i> And show him the way,</i><br><i> Lest he be trapped forever </i><br><i> On public display.</i><br> &#160;<br><i> If he loses this chance </i><br><i> To rise and depart, </i><br><i> All magic will fade</i><br><i> From his horn and his heart.</i><br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;A unicorn!&rdquo; breathed Annie. &ldquo;I love him already. <i>I&rsquo;ll</i> show him the way!&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;But this poem is really hard to understand,&rdquo; said Jack. &ldquo;What kind of research book did Morgan send us?&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> He picked up the book that had been left for them by Morgan le Fay, the librarian of Camelot. The cover showed a row of skyscrapers. The title was <i>New York City Guide Book, 1938</i>.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;New York City?&rdquo; said Annie. &ldquo;I love New York City! Remember the great time we had there with Aunt Mallory?&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Yeah, I love it, too,&rdquo; said Jack. &ldquo;But why would there be a unicorn in New York City in 1938? A unicorn is an ancient fantasy creature. New York City&rsquo;s a real place, and 1938 is not even that long ago.&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;You&rsquo;re right,&rdquo; said Annie. &ldquo;It sounds like a hard mission. But don&rsquo;t forget we have Teddy and Kathleen&rsquo;s magic rhymes to help us.&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Yeah,&rdquo; said Jack. He pulled out the book given to them by their friends Teddy and Kathleen, two young enchanters of Camelot. &ldquo;The problem is, we can only use each rhyme once, and we&rsquo;ve already used seven out of the ten.&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Which means we still have three left,&rdquo; said Annie. &ldquo;What are they?&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;<i>Pull a Cloud from the Sky</i>,&rdquo; said Jack. <br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Cool,&rdquo; said Annie.<br> &ldquo;Yeah, it is,&rdquo; said Jack. &ldquo;But I&rsquo;m not sure it will be much use.&rdquo; He looked back at the book. &ldquo;<i>Find a Treasure You Must Never Lose</i>,&rdquo; he said. <br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Hey, that&rsquo;s a really good one!&rdquo; said Annie. &ldquo;The unicorn&rsquo;s a treasure. So that rhyme could<br> take care of our whole mission.&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;But it only partly fits,&rdquo; said Jack. &ldquo;You could call the unicorn a treasure. But once we find him, we have to lose him. He has to go back home.&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Oh, right... ,&rdquo; said Annie. &ldquo;What else?&rdquo; <br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Your favorite,&rdquo; said Jack. &ldquo;<i>Turn into Ducks</i>.&rdquo; <br> &#160;<br> Annie laughed. &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t wait to use that one!&rdquo; she said.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;I hope we <i>never</i> use that one,&rdquo; said Jack. He didn&rsquo;t want to waddle around and quack like a duck. &ldquo;These leftover rhymes don&rsquo;t seem very helpful to me.&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> &ldquo;Well, let&rsquo;s just wait and see,&rdquo; said Annie. &ldquo;But now . . . &rdquo; She held up Morgan&rsquo;s research book and smiled.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> Jack nodded. &ldquo;New York City, here we come,&rdquo; he said. He pointed at the book&rsquo;s cover. &ldquo;I wish we could go <i>there</i>!&rdquo;<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> The wind started to blow.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> The tree house started to spin. It spun faster and faster.<br> &#160;<br> &#160;<br> Then everything was still. Absolutely still.",
